00:05:03.250 --> 00:05:14.790
So, perhaps the most over-rated or over-hyped
idea in the social sciences in the last 70

00:05:14.790 --> 00:05:19.340
years has been the idea that people are basically
selfish.

00:05:19.340 --> 00:05:22.260
That our fundamental nature is selfish.

00:05:22.260 --> 00:05:24.140
Economists have told us that for decades.

00:05:24.140 --> 00:05:28.370
Political scientists have told us that people
vote for their self-interest.

00:05:28.370 --> 00:05:32.800
Evolutionists, such as Richard Dawkins told
us about selfish genes.

00:05:32.800 --> 00:05:37.470
Which, they can make us cooperate with our
kin in cases of reciprocity.

00:05:37.470 --> 00:05:42.080
But by and large as Dawkins said, "let us
try to teach generosity and altruism because

00:05:42.080 --> 00:05:43.780
we are born selfish."

00:05:43.780 --> 00:05:49.980
George Williams, one of the greatest evolutionary
biologists, said it even more bluntly.

00:05:49.980 --> 00:05:56.210
"Morality is an accidental capability produced,
in its boundless stupidity, by a biological

00:05:56.210 --> 00:05:59.780
process that is normally opposed to the expression
of such a capability."

00:05:59.780 --> 00:06:03.280
So the view is, human nature is selfish.

00:06:03.280 --> 00:06:07.750
We can transcend it, we can act in ways that
go against our fundamental nature, but our

00:06:07.750 --> 00:06:10.250
fundamental nature is selfish.

00:06:10.250 --> 00:06:15.370
Now, this view has been widely embraced in
business schools and the business community

00:06:15.370 --> 00:06:18.220
and it's been embraced even more strongly
by people who hate business.

00:06:18.220 --> 00:06:22.550
Here's an essay that was published in The
New York Times last week, "Capitalists and

00:06:22.550 --> 00:06:24.130
Other Psychopaths".

00:06:24.130 --> 00:06:28.850
It reported, down at the bottom you can see
it reported when it came out in paper it said

00:06:28.850 --> 00:06:34.650
"2010 study found that 10% of a sample of
corporate managers met a clinical threshold

00:06:34.650 --> 00:06:36.130
for being labeled 'psychopaths'".

00:06:36.130 --> 00:06:39.880
I read that and I said "that's nonsense, it
can't possibly be true".

00:06:39.880 --> 00:06:41.800
And I was right, the guy just made up that
number.

00:06:41.800 --> 00:06:45.770
The actual study that he was quoting said
4% which is even still probably too high.

00:06:45.770 --> 00:06:50.880
But the point is that there's a narrative
out there about business which is that it

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:54.730
is a bunch of psychopaths and that explains
why businesses act the way they act.

00:06:54.730 --> 00:06:59.000
It's because of that narrative, that long
standing narrative which I suppose goes back

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:05.090
to the 19th century that Google, of course,
came up with its identity, its brand.

00:07:05.090 --> 00:07:08.840
Which is "Don't be evil", but then of course,
people being what they are, there are many

00:07:08.840 --> 00:07:12.750
cynics on the web who think that Google is
evil.

00:07:12.750 --> 00:07:20.560
[laughter]
So, now my talk today is about how our nature

00:07:20.560 --> 00:07:21.560
is other than this.

00:07:21.560 --> 00:07:25.460
Our nature is not entirely selfish.

00:07:25.460 --> 00:07:28.660
There's been a kind of a little boomlet in
the last 10 years or so on altruism.

00:07:28.660 --> 00:07:33.430
A lot of people reject this idea and want
to prove no people are deeply altruistic.

00:07:33.430 --> 00:07:36.890
And there are cases like Mother Theresa, although
from her biography, as I understand it, even

00:07:36.890 --> 00:07:39.380
Mother Theresa wasn't exactly like Mother
Theresa.

00:07:39.380 --> 00:07:43.150
But there are cases of people who devote themselves
to helping others.

00:07:43.150 --> 00:07:46.120
That's interesting but I think actually that's
not really where the action is.

00:07:46.120 --> 00:07:50.250
If you wanna understand what's so amazing
about human beings, don't go looking for all

00:07:50.250 --> 00:07:53.750
the cases where we do extreme acts of altruism
for strangers.

00:07:53.750 --> 00:07:57.860
Rather, what's really remarkable about us
is our extraordinary cooperation.

00:07:57.860 --> 00:08:02.430
We're just really cooperative, you guys have
all cooperated more than a hundred times since

00:08:02.430 --> 00:08:03.520
breakfast.

00:08:03.520 --> 00:08:06.470
It's just when you walk in the hallway, when
you drive on the road, we are all cooperating

00:08:06.470 --> 00:08:07.800
all the time.

00:08:07.800 --> 00:08:12.800
There's a particular kind of cooperation I'll
focus on which I'll call "groupishness" and

00:08:12.800 --> 00:08:17.500
I'm calling it this to be able to make a very
precise comparison to selfishness.

00:08:17.500 --> 00:08:22.510
Because when I say, as a psychologist, that
we are selfish, that our nature is in part

00:08:22.510 --> 00:08:28.890
selfish, what I mean is that the human mind
contains a variety of mental mechanisms that

00:08:28.890 --> 00:08:33.970
make us adept at promoting our own interests
in competition with our peers.

00:08:33.970 --> 00:08:35.970
Of course, we're good at that.

00:08:35.970 --> 00:08:40.800
Of course, we evolved these complex minds
that make us selfish very often.

00:08:40.800 --> 00:08:41.860
I'm not arguing that.

00:08:41.860 --> 00:08:44.560
What I'm arguing is that's not the whole story.

00:08:44.560 --> 00:08:51.700
We are also groupish, by which I mean our
minds contain a variety of mental mechanisms

00:08:51.700 --> 00:08:57.650
that make us adept at promoting our group's
interests in competition with other groups.

00:08:57.650 --> 00:09:02.170
I'm arguing that we focus too much, in the
social sciences, on the competition of individual

00:09:02.170 --> 00:09:06.130
versus individual and not enough on the competition
of group versus group.

00:09:06.130 --> 00:09:07.740
Which I believe has also shaped our mind.

00:09:07.740 --> 00:09:11.990
That's a side story about multi-level selection,
group selection versus individual selection.

00:09:11.990 --> 00:09:13.350
We don't need to get into that today.

00:09:13.350 --> 00:09:15.940
But that's the background to part of what
I'm saying here.

00:09:15.940 --> 00:09:16.940
[clears throat]

00:09:16.940 --> 00:09:22.130
So, the reason I believe this, the reason
I began studying groupishness as a moral psychologist

00:09:22.130 --> 00:09:25.950
that is I'm a social psychologist, but I specialize
in the study of morality.

00:09:25.950 --> 00:09:31.760
The reason I study this is because I was studying
the moral emotions, like moral elevation and

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:37.560
I just found there are so many ways that people
have found to shut down their selves, shut

00:09:37.560 --> 00:09:40.890
down self-interest, transcend the self.

00:09:40.890 --> 00:09:45.710
The metaphor that I'll use is that it's as
though there's a staircase in our minds and

00:09:45.710 --> 00:09:49.830
there's a kind of a door that sometimes opens,
very rarely, but most of us have had it open.

00:09:49.830 --> 00:09:55.770
There's a kind of door that opens, it's as
though there is kind of a secret staircase,

00:09:55.770 --> 00:10:06.840
and when this door opens, it invites us to
go up, we climb the stair case and we emerge

00:10:06.840 --> 00:10:08.620
into a different realm.

00:10:08.620 --> 00:10:12.840
A realm in which we are fundamentally different.

00:10:12.840 --> 00:10:18.820
We transcend ourselves and it isn't just different,
it's ecstatic, it feels wonderful.

00:10:18.820 --> 00:10:22.870
Most of us are familiar with these experiences
in nature.

00:10:22.870 --> 00:10:27.440
Raise your hand if you have ever climbed a
mountain or gone out in nature specifically

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:30.870
to experience some sort of an altered state
of consciousness, a state of self-transcendence,

00:10:30.870 --> 00:10:31.870
please raise your hand.

00:10:31.870 --> 00:10:35.500
OK, so right, especially here in Northern
California, you kind of stumble out to get

00:10:35.500 --> 00:10:37.460
the milk and that seems to happen to you.

00:10:37.460 --> 00:10:38.860
But anyway.

00:10:38.860 --> 00:10:41.600
Most of us are familiar with this kind of
experience.

00:10:41.600 --> 00:10:45.660
Ralph Waldo Emerson described it, I think,
in the most eloquent way that it has even

00:10:45.660 --> 00:10:47.720
been described.

00:10:47.720 --> 00:10:51.140
Just describing what it's like to go for a
walk in the woods in New England.

00:10:51.140 --> 00:10:56.880
And I've had some animators animate his words,
these are from an essay from, I think, 1839

00:10:56.880 --> 00:11:02.430
and again, it's as though this staircase opens,
the door opens, you go up the staircase and

00:11:02.430 --> 00:11:04.090
here's what he said about it.

00:11:04.090 --> 00:11:11.360
&gt;&gt;male narrator: In the woods these plantations
of God, a decorum and sanctity reign.

00:11:11.360 --> 00:11:17.310
Standing on the bare ground, my head bathed
by the blithe air, and uplifted into infinite

00:11:17.310 --> 00:11:21.750
space, all mean egotism vanishes.

00:11:21.750 --> 00:11:32.120
I become a transparent eyeball, I am nothing,
I see all.

00:11:32.120 --> 00:11:37.170
The currents of the Universal Being circulate
through me.

00:11:37.170 --> 00:11:41.100
I am the lover of uncontained and immortal
beauty.

00:11:41.100 --> 00:11:48.530
&gt;&gt; Dr. Jonathan Haidt: So, he had lines like
"all mean egotism vanishes" again, this self-transcendent

00:11:48.530 --> 00:11:51.970
nature of nature experiences.

00:11:51.970 --> 00:11:55.590
William James, one of the founders of American
psychology, wrote a book called "Varieties

00:11:55.590 --> 00:12:00.740
of Religious Experience" were he cataloged
all these sorts of experiences and he noted

00:12:00.740 --> 00:12:03.890
that they don't just make us happy; they don't
just make us feel good.

00:12:03.890 --> 00:12:05.560
They make us feel different.

00:12:05.560 --> 00:12:07.760
That our self is fundamentally changed.

00:12:07.760 --> 00:12:11.100
People don't come back from these experiences
saying "I can do anything.

00:12:11.100 --> 00:12:14.590
Now I'm going to make as much money as I can
as quickly as I can."

00:12:14.590 --> 00:12:19.920
Rather, they come back experiencing a moral
commitment and a desire to serve, to be part

00:12:19.920 --> 00:12:23.610
of something larger.

00:12:23.610 --> 00:12:27.800
Many of the world's religions have developed
techniques and technologies to foster these

00:12:27.800 --> 00:12:30.370
self-transcendent experiences.

00:12:30.370 --> 00:12:35.990
Meditation is one developed especially in
most of the eastern religions.

00:12:35.990 --> 00:12:39.420
Many of the world's religions discovered psychedelic
drugs.

00:12:39.420 --> 00:12:44.350
Substances that can, within 30 minutes, attain
the kind of self-transcendence that takes

00:12:44.350 --> 00:12:46.610
years of study through meditation to achieve.

00:12:46.610 --> 00:12:53.090
This is from a sixteenth century scroll showing
a mushroom eater about to consume a mushroom.

00:12:53.090 --> 00:12:57.430
And as soon as he eats it, this god is going
to yank him up the staircase into the other

00:12:57.430 --> 00:12:58.430
world.

00:12:58.430 --> 00:13:03.150
We don't know much about the Aztec's religion
and to what degree it was a moral transformation.

00:13:03.150 --> 00:13:07.040
But in the '60s there was a great deal of
interest in psychedelic drugs, there was research

00:13:07.040 --> 00:13:08.040
on it.

00:13:08.040 --> 00:13:13.870
A famous study by Walter Pahnke, in conjunction
with Timothy Leary, gave psilocybin or niacin

00:13:13.870 --> 00:13:14.870
pills.

00:13:14.870 --> 00:13:16.720
It was a placebo controlled study.

00:13:16.720 --> 00:13:22.250
They gave the pills to divinity students in
a basement in a chapel at Boston University.

00:13:22.250 --> 00:13:28.930
And all 10 of the students who took psilocybin
had religious experiences and those who took

00:13:28.930 --> 00:13:33.020
niacin, they first felt a flush, you feel
like something is happening, they were really

00:13:33.020 --> 00:13:34.020
psyched.

00:13:34.020 --> 00:13:35.100
They said "Yes, I'm one of those who got the
pill."

00:13:35.100 --> 00:13:38.850
But it was just niacin and that quickly faded
and nothing else happened.

00:13:38.850 --> 00:13:45.250
So the subjects who got psilocybin experienced
profound transformations, as one of them put

00:13:45.250 --> 00:13:50.380
it "feelings of connectedness with everybody
and everything".

00:13:50.380 --> 00:13:56.950
So again, these many many roots of self-transcendence
which have a morally transformative effect,

00:13:56.950 --> 00:13:59.380
this is what I'm interested in.

00:13:59.380 --> 00:14:03.871
Many of the world's religions use circling,
rhythmic movements to create an altered state

00:14:03.871 --> 00:14:06.839
in which one gets closer to God.

