our and individual fate lose its central importance.

00:15:29.600 --> 00:15:37.270
I believe that it is nothing less than the
assurance of immortality that makes self-sacrifice

00:15:37.270 --> 00:15:39.430
at these moments so relatively easy.

00:15:39.430 --> 00:15:43.880
"I may fall, but I do not die.

00:15:43.880 --> 00:15:50.050
For that which is real in me goes forward
and lives on in the comrades for whom I gave

00:15:50.050 --> 00:15:51.050
up my life"

00:15:51.050 --> 00:15:56.920
&gt;&gt; Dr. Jonathan Haidt: "I" passes insensibly
into "we", "my" becomes "our" and individual

00:15:56.920 --> 00:16:00.050
fate lose its central importance.

00:16:00.050 --> 00:16:04.630
If bees could speak, I think this is the sort
of thing that they would say.

00:16:04.630 --> 00:16:08.430
So it's because of these experiences, they
are so ubiquitous; you find them all over

00:16:08.430 --> 00:16:10.930
the world, across the eons.

00:16:10.930 --> 00:16:13.649
It's as though we were designed to be able
to lose ourselves.

00:16:13.649 --> 00:16:17.899
At very least there's something in our minds
that makes it easy to do so.

00:16:17.899 --> 00:16:21.910
This is what led me to formulate what I called
the hive psychology hypothesis.

00:16:21.910 --> 00:16:28.800
It's a hypothesis, but my claim is that human
nature, alright this parts a metaphor, not

00:16:28.800 --> 00:16:29.800
a hypothesis.

00:16:29.800 --> 00:16:33.600
Human nature is 90% chimp, 10% bee.

00:16:33.600 --> 00:16:34.760
That's the metaphor.

00:16:34.760 --> 00:16:40.089
The idea is that most of our sociality is
strategic or selfish.

00:16:40.089 --> 00:16:45.360
When you read books on human nature or evolution
where they invariably compare to other animals

00:16:45.360 --> 00:16:49.770
and the author will trace out kin selection,
reciprocal altruism.

00:16:49.770 --> 00:16:56.610
So we're able to cooperate as other animals
are but it's ultimately for our own benefit.

00:16:56.610 --> 00:17:02.089
Just like chimpanzees, but we have the ability
to forget our self-interest and lose ourselves

00:17:02.089 --> 00:17:05.660
in something larger than ourselves, like bees.

00:17:05.660 --> 00:17:12.089
My claim here is that we are like bees, in
part because we went through a parallel process

00:17:12.089 --> 00:17:13.630
of evolution as bees did.

00:17:13.630 --> 00:17:16.550
Namely a long period of group versus group
competition.

00:17:16.550 --> 00:17:20.230
Which chimps didn't really go through, or
our primate ancestors didn't go through.

00:17:20.230 --> 00:17:22.450
But group selected species do.

00:17:22.450 --> 00:17:26.870
So, we're very good in situations that call
for every man for himself.

00:17:26.870 --> 00:17:30.720
This is a photo of a tomato fight in Spain,
everybody throws tomatoes at everybody.

00:17:30.720 --> 00:17:34.251
But, I would note, they had to actually all
get together and agree on the rules, get a

00:17:34.251 --> 00:17:36.390
permit you know they're all having fun.

00:17:36.390 --> 00:17:39.110
So actually even this isn't every man for
himself.

00:17:39.110 --> 00:17:41.990
But, we're good at it, we can do that.

00:17:41.990 --> 00:17:45.670
But we are especially good at one for all,
all for one.

00:17:45.670 --> 00:17:48.010
Alright, how does that happen?

00:17:48.010 --> 00:17:54.059
Well, let's look at sociality, let's step
back and look at what forms sociality takes

00:17:54.059 --> 00:17:55.780
in the animal kingdom.

00:17:55.780 --> 00:17:57.450
Many many animals are social.

00:17:57.450 --> 00:18:02.429
Darwin wrote about this and noted that it's
often adaptive to hang out with others, not

00:18:02.429 --> 00:18:06.120
because they work together as a team but because
the odds are that you won't be the slowest

00:18:06.120 --> 00:18:07.440
out of the thousand deer.

00:18:07.440 --> 00:18:11.390
And so when the lion comes, it will be your
neighbor that gets eaten, and not you.

00:18:11.390 --> 00:18:17.900
So, deer are like this, they live in herds
and these herds are not cooperative at all.

00:18:17.900 --> 00:18:20.220
It's just safety in numbers, there's no team
work.

00:18:20.220 --> 00:18:23.679
So this does not provide a good metaphor for
anything in the corporate world.

00:18:23.679 --> 00:18:26.210
I don't think there are any corporations that
are herds.

00:18:26.210 --> 00:18:28.640
Alright, but let's move up a little bit.

00:18:28.640 --> 00:18:30.820
A lot of animals live in packs.

00:18:30.820 --> 00:18:32.310
Now packs are very different.

00:18:32.310 --> 00:18:37.960
Packs, you especially find them among carnivores
because teamwork lets them take down larger

00:18:37.960 --> 00:18:39.450
prey.

00:18:39.450 --> 00:18:44.120
Four wolves working together can take down
a much larger animal.

00:18:44.120 --> 00:18:49.820
But, a wolf pack is a rough place to be, there's
constant competition for status and resources.

00:18:49.820 --> 00:18:52.500
Well, now it's beginning to sound more familiar.

00:18:52.500 --> 00:18:58.790
So familiar in fact that many textbooks of
organizational behavior specifically feature

00:18:58.790 --> 00:18:59.790
wolves.

00:18:59.790 --> 00:19:03.520
And we train our MBA students to be effective
wolves.

00:19:03.520 --> 00:19:07.680
Most MBA companies can be analogized to wolf
packs.

00:19:07.680 --> 00:19:09.270
Teamwork lets them take down larger prey.

00:19:09.270 --> 00:19:13.720
They can do things they could not do as individuals
but there's constant competition for status

00:19:13.720 --> 00:19:14.850
and resources.

00:19:14.850 --> 00:19:18.250
So that works, that works throughout most
of the business world.

