00:19:32.640 --> 00:19:34.650
which is hives.

00:19:34.650 --> 00:19:38.841
Only a few kinds of species live in hives,
it's only been discovered a few times in the

00:19:38.841 --> 00:19:39.930
evolution of life on earth.

00:19:39.930 --> 00:19:41.360
A few dozen times actually.

00:19:41.360 --> 00:19:44.730
The Hymenoptera were the main discoverers
of this way of living.

00:19:44.730 --> 00:19:50.620
The bees, wasps and ants and they are able
to live in gigantic colonies with massive

00:19:50.620 --> 00:19:54.400
division of labor, and they are able to do
it because they are all sisters.

00:19:54.400 --> 00:19:58.170
They suppress breeding, so they're really
all in the same boat, all in the same hive.

00:19:58.170 --> 00:20:01.120
It's one for all, all for one.

00:20:01.120 --> 00:20:07.090
There was a species of cockroach that discovered
this form of living and their bodies morphed

00:20:07.090 --> 00:20:08.470
into those that we now call termites.

00:20:08.470 --> 00:20:12.300
And there's one species of mammal that did,
the naked mole rat.

00:20:12.300 --> 00:20:15.760
In all five of these cases, it's the same
trick.

00:20:15.760 --> 00:20:19.390
Suppress breeding, so that you have just one
queen who lays all the eggs or gives birth

00:20:19.390 --> 00:20:23.751
to all the babies and now everybody's interest,
their biological interest is one for all,

00:20:23.751 --> 00:20:24.751
all for one.

00:20:24.751 --> 00:20:27.250
Keep the queen alive, keep the babies alive.

00:20:27.250 --> 00:20:31.460
And so they're able to cooperate, massively
build gigantic nests, thousands of times larger

00:20:31.460 --> 00:20:32.790
than any individual.

00:20:32.790 --> 00:20:36.630
It's really quite extraordinary what they
can do, but it's not hard to explain because

00:20:36.630 --> 00:20:39.450
it's straight kinship.

00:20:39.450 --> 00:20:46.080
Now, once you get hive living, you can get
this amazing division of labor and you can

00:20:46.080 --> 00:20:48.580
the group functioning as a super organism.

00:20:48.580 --> 00:20:53.740
This is an image of giant Asian honey bees
that do this behavior.

00:20:53.740 --> 00:20:58.270
And what scientists have figured out is that
they do this when there is a wasp, a larger

00:20:58.270 --> 00:21:01.301
predatory insect, there's a wasp trying to
get in.

00:21:01.301 --> 00:21:04.540
Trying to attack them, to get in, trying to
get the honey.

00:21:04.540 --> 00:21:10.760
So, they're able to flick their tails and
their bodies in unison, in a pattern that

00:21:10.760 --> 00:21:13.710
basically flicks the wasp off.

00:21:13.710 --> 00:21:18.591
It's an amazing feat of coordination possible
because they live in this way, one for all,

00:21:18.591 --> 00:21:19.591
all for one.

00:21:19.591 --> 00:21:24.390
And these emergent behaviors have evolved,
quite extraordinary.

00:21:24.390 --> 00:21:29.260
This yields massive efficiency; you have massive
division of labor and trust.

00:21:29.260 --> 00:21:34.160
Is this an analogy or even a homology for
anything in the corporate world?

00:21:34.160 --> 00:21:36.670
Are there any businesses that work this way?

00:21:36.670 --> 00:21:42.400
Well, there's no business that has no competition,
in which people are truly perfect hive members,

00:21:42.400 --> 00:21:44.410
where there's no politics, no competition.

00:21:44.410 --> 00:21:47.390
But there are many businesses that come close.

00:21:47.390 --> 00:21:52.880
I've visited a couple times at zappos.com
and they pride themselves in being like this,

00:21:52.880 --> 00:21:54.140
and my sense is that they really are.

00:21:54.140 --> 00:21:58.670
If you put Zappos into Google image search,
this was one of the first images that came

00:21:58.670 --> 00:22:01.179
up when I did this.

00:22:01.179 --> 00:22:05.880
And it is them forming this symbol of one
for all, all for one and when they do this

00:22:05.880 --> 00:22:08.750
love to spin around like those bees.

00:22:08.750 --> 00:22:13.450
So, some companies, I think, are like this.

00:22:13.450 --> 00:22:17.230
Now, I want to tell you about this little
bit of research that has been done on hive

00:22:17.230 --> 00:22:18.690
psychology recently.

00:22:18.690 --> 00:22:24.590
It's been discovered that synchronous movement,
moving together, seems to change our minds,

00:22:24.590 --> 00:22:29.750
chance our physiology in ways that make us
extra good hive members.

00:22:29.750 --> 00:22:33.520
So, many religions use synchronous movement
well.

00:22:33.520 --> 00:22:38.860
Scott Wiltermuth and Chip Heath at the Stanford
Business School, brought people into the lab,

00:22:38.860 --> 00:22:43.110
had them basically sing a drinking song.

00:22:43.110 --> 00:22:46.590
They didn't actually give them alcohol but
