00:30:39.620 --> 00:30:42.500
and people are emphasizing their similarity.

00:30:42.500 --> 00:30:46.390
On the other hand, at least what I heard at
Zappos, and what I've also heard from a student

00:30:46.390 --> 00:30:49.970
of mine, Jesse Kluver who is a Marine, is
that when you have a really hivish group,

00:30:49.970 --> 00:30:54.700
there is such trust and everybody values the
mission that actually, often what you have

00:30:54.700 --> 00:30:59.230
is it's easier to speak up because everyone
trusts that you're not grandstanding, you

00:30:59.230 --> 00:31:01.460
really have the interest of the group at heart.

00:31:01.460 --> 00:31:08.860
So, it's an open question when hivishness
will have a profile of benefits and when it

00:31:08.860 --> 00:31:10.700
will have costs.

00:31:10.700 --> 00:31:16.450
Now, some advice on what one can do if you
have an organization, this is not just true

00:31:16.450 --> 00:31:21.330
in the corporate world, this is any organization
any non-profit a soccer team, anything.

00:31:21.330 --> 00:31:25.870
Well, some of the basic ideas from classic
social psychology are that when people have

00:31:25.870 --> 00:31:29.440
a sense of shared fate, and especially a sense
of shared sacrifice.

00:31:29.440 --> 00:31:32.470
We're all pulling together; we're all in the
same boat.

00:31:32.470 --> 00:31:37.820
That really brings out the bee in us; it really
brings out the cooperator in us.

00:31:37.820 --> 00:31:42.860
It's very important in any organization to
suppress free riders if there's a sense, because

00:31:42.860 --> 00:31:45.980
in such an organization there's so much freedom.

00:31:45.980 --> 00:31:50.429
Anybody who wanted to could stock up on all
these snacks and go sell them on the street

00:31:50.429 --> 00:31:52.059
corner if you wanted to.

00:31:52.059 --> 00:31:57.480
And anybody who did that would be violating
the group's trust.

00:31:57.480 --> 00:32:03.659
Any organization that lets free riders do
such things then suddenly activates more negative

00:32:03.659 --> 00:32:06.780
psychology in everybody else, people don't
feel that they can trust each other.

00:32:06.780 --> 00:32:09.159
So free riders are really poisonous.

00:32:09.159 --> 00:32:12.100
It's crucial that free riders be punished
and punished quickly.

00:32:12.100 --> 00:32:16.790
But punishment doesn't have to involve spanking
or firing or anything else.

00:32:16.790 --> 00:32:18.960
Gossip is the normal human form of punishment.

00:32:18.960 --> 00:32:23.929
Gossip is actually, generally speaking a good
thing, especially in a hivish organization.

00:32:23.929 --> 00:32:27.929
Gossip gets a bad name because in junior high
school people tend to use it to destroy their

00:32:27.929 --> 00:32:28.929
rivals.

00:32:28.929 --> 00:32:29.929
So that's ugly.

00:32:29.929 --> 00:32:37.070
But, what's been found, a study by Naft and
Wilson, looked at gossip on a crew team.

00:32:37.070 --> 00:32:40.559
And when you have a group working together
like that, most of the gossip was actually

00:32:40.559 --> 00:32:43.429
who's shirking, who's not working out hard
enough.

00:32:43.429 --> 00:32:47.309
When people really care about the mission
of the group they tend to gossip in way that's

00:32:47.309 --> 00:32:52.190
will shame and punish those who are drifting
off and sort of pull them back in.

00:32:52.190 --> 00:32:57.170
So gossip is the front line of defense for
a healthy organization.

00:32:57.170 --> 00:33:01.809
Third, heightened similarity, anything that
makes you feel like you are all one will help

00:33:01.809 --> 00:33:02.940
this feeling.

00:33:02.940 --> 00:33:05.720
So of course many companies emphasize diversity.

00:33:05.720 --> 00:33:12.309
It's important to emphasize diversity for
justice reasons and diversity especially of

00:33:12.309 --> 00:33:16.000
perspectives, has many benefits for creativity.

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:21.620
But I want to emphasize that to get trust
and cohesion, you don't want to tell everyone

00:33:21.620 --> 00:33:24.679
oh, we're all so different and that's great,
you want to say we're all the same.

00:33:24.679 --> 00:33:28.400
And when you do that race stops mattering
because so many other things link you together.

00:33:28.400 --> 00:33:33.650
So, just think about emphasizing similarity
not diversity.

00:33:33.650 --> 00:33:38.690
Fourth point, synchrony moving together to
the extent possible, has been shown to have

00:33:38.690 --> 00:33:39.830
these effects.

00:33:39.830 --> 00:33:41.900
Healthy competition is good.

00:33:41.900 --> 00:33:47.400
When you divide people into groups, they tend
to trust the people in their group more and

00:33:47.400 --> 00:33:50.180
interestingly, they don't dislike the people
in the other group.

00:33:50.180 --> 00:33:52.860
So, are there any intramural competitions
here?

00:33:52.860 --> 00:33:55.960
Is there any time where you do group versus
group or division versus division here at

00:33:55.960 --> 00:33:56.960
Google?

00:33:56.960 --> 00:33:58.500
Do you ever do that?

00:33:58.500 --> 00:34:01.659
I assume you don't then hate the people on
the other team?

00:34:01.659 --> 00:34:02.659
It's playful, it's fun.

00:34:02.659 --> 00:34:04.350
You get to work together more closely.

00:34:04.350 --> 00:34:08.559
So this is the classic social psych finding,
in-group love is not purchased at the cost

00:34:08.559 --> 00:34:10.230
of out-group hate.

00:34:10.230 --> 00:34:13.999
Unless the competition gets really nasty,
and then it gets viciously tribal and that's

00:34:13.999 --> 00:34:15.889
where we are in the US Congress.

00:34:15.889 --> 00:34:18.849
But within a healthy company that's not what
happens.

00:34:18.849 --> 00:34:24.170
Lastly, to the extent that you can say your
company is pursuing a noble mission, it's

00:34:24.170 --> 00:34:26.240
much easier to inspire people.

00:34:26.240 --> 00:34:30.079
So at Zappos, for example, they don't talk
about selling shoes, they talk about their

00:34:30.079 --> 00:34:31.589
mission is delivering happiness.

00:34:31.589 --> 00:34:34.149
They're a service company.

00:34:34.149 --> 00:34:36.059
And Google is organizing the world's information.

00:34:36.059 --> 00:34:37.419
Google is making our lives easier.

00:34:37.419 --> 00:34:39.059
Google is doing all these wonderful things.

00:34:39.059 --> 00:34:44.879
So, to the extent that one is thinking about
the culture of one's team or organization,

00:34:44.879 --> 00:34:48.039
these are some pointers for how to make it
more hivish and cooperative.

00:34:48.039 --> 00:34:52.269
There are some specific things that leaders
can do, behaving in particular with integrity

00:34:52.269 --> 00:34:53.730
and charisma.

00:34:53.730 --> 00:34:57.170
A leader must be worth of respect, admiration
and perhaps even awe.

00:34:57.170 --> 00:34:59.410
Not necessarily but these things do help.

00:34:59.410 --> 00:35:04.749
Great leaders, such as Julius Caesar, inspired
their men because their followers could trust

00:35:04.749 --> 00:35:05.749
them.

00:35:05.749 --> 00:35:06.749
They looked up to them.

00:35:06.749 --> 00:35:10.440
One of the most important things about being
a leader or a boss is that people are willing

00:35:10.440 --> 00:35:16.680
to cede you authority and to follow you as
long as they trust that you really are out

00:35:16.680 --> 00:35:17.869
for the good of the group.

00:35:17.869 --> 00:35:21.789
As soon as they get the sense that you're
a self-aggrandizer, that you're out for yourself

00:35:21.789 --> 00:35:27.200
or you've got your favorites and you're out
for your faction and not going to help the

00:35:27.200 --> 00:35:30.510
other members of team, then they'll turn against
you very, very quickly.

00:35:30.510 --> 00:35:35.460
So an important part of leadership is impartiality,
fairness, people really have to trust you,

00:35:35.460 --> 00:35:36.460
that you're really impartial.

00:35:36.460 --> 00:35:41.799
And then they will accept decisions from you
that work against their self-interest.

00:35:41.799 --> 00:35:45.530
Self-sacrifice is crucial, that leaders sacrifice
when times are tough.

00:35:45.530 --> 00:35:50.680
I was at a, there was a positive psychology
conference, a month after 9/11 and corporate

00:35:50.680 --> 00:35:57.569
CEO got up and said to this room of 300 psychologists
"We, the business community, we are on the

00:35:57.569 --> 00:35:59.329
front line in the fight against terror."

00:35:59.329 --> 00:36:02.810
Which seems to me to be incredibly pompous
when we are sending troops over to Afghanistan

00:36:02.810 --> 00:36:05.320
to actually fight and face bullets, but anyway.

00:36:05.320 --> 00:36:08.839
So, "we CEOs are on the front line of the
fight against terror, and we need ideas from

00:36:08.839 --> 00:36:15.480
you as to what we can do and how we can win
this fight" So I stood up and I said "Well,

00:36:15.480 --> 00:36:21.520
we've just gone through the 90s when CEO pay
skyrocketed as profits were going up.

00:36:21.520 --> 00:36:25.369
Now the economies turned and 9/11's pushed
us down further, profits are dropping, pay

00:36:25.369 --> 00:36:26.369
is dropping.

00:36:26.369 --> 00:36:31.989
So, I would think if CEOs would take a massive
cut in pay on the way down, that would inspire

00:36:31.989 --> 00:36:34.520
more cooperation and help you win the fight
against terror."

00:36:34.520 --> 00:36:35.520
[Audience laughs]

00:36:35.520 --> 00:36:39.140
&gt;&gt; Dr. Jonathan Haidt: He says "That isn't
helpful, any other suggestions?"

00:36:39.140 --> 00:36:42.339
[laughter] So anyway, shared sacrifice.

00:36:42.339 --> 00:36:49.079
And lastly eloquence, history books are full
of times when a battle turned or the history

00:36:49.079 --> 00:36:53.569
of the world turned on one person giving an
inspiring and eloquent speech that rallied

00:36:53.569 --> 00:36:56.869
others to work or fight their hardest.

00:36:56.869 --> 00:37:02.450
So to conclude, we have this story about human
beings being fundamentally selfish.

00:37:02.450 --> 00:37:08.259
And certainly businesses and business people
being fundamentally selfish and while I think

00:37:08.259 --> 00:37:11.269
there is a little bit of truth to this, this
story does work in some corners of the business

00:37:11.269 --> 00:37:12.269
world.

00:37:12.269 --> 00:37:14.969
And right now we're all trying to figure out
whether the finance business, the finance

00:37:14.969 --> 00:37:18.650
industry is different from the rest of the
corporate world where they actually make things

00:37:18.650 --> 00:37:21.009
that are of use to people.

00:37:21.009 --> 00:37:24.329
Finance does seem to be plagued by many more
problems than other areas of the business

00:37:24.329 --> 00:37:25.329
world.

00:37:25.329 --> 00:37:31.219
But I'd like to replace this idea of human
nature with this idea: that we are both selfish

00:37:31.219 --> 00:37:37.509
and cooperative, we are selfish and groupish,
and I think this is not just a more inspiring

00:37:37.509 --> 00:37:41.099
of what we are but I think it's actually a
true vision.

00:37:41.099 --> 00:37:43.490
Thank you very much.

00:37:43.490 --> 00:37:45.599
[Applause]

00:37:45.599 --> 00:37:52.680
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: We have time for questions,
so if you're interested come up to the microphone

00:37:52.680 --> 00:37:54.719
and ask away.

00:37:54.719 --> 00:38:01.469
&gt;&gt;male #1: So you've made some pretty compelling
arguments about the benefits of hivishness

00:38:01.469 --> 00:38:04.029
and the human propensity for hivishness.

00:38:04.029 --> 00:38:08.999
And given those benefits, it seems reasonable
that people would have this psychological

00:38:08.999 --> 00:38:10.690
propensity.

00:38:10.690 --> 00:38:18.119
But we all know that evolution is not a teleological
mechanism that seeks long term global optimization-

00:38:18.119 --> 00:38:19.119
&gt;&gt;Dr. Jonathan Haidt: Not at all.

00:38:19.119 --> 00:38:22.759
&gt;&gt;male #1: -and in fact you cited the fact
that a lot of the insects have to adopt these

00:38:22.759 --> 00:38:28.690
very strange genetic patterns into their hives
in order to make it evolutionarily stable

00:38:28.690 --> 00:38:32.609
strategy for them to behave that way.

00:38:32.609 --> 00:38:36.249
You said at the beginning you didn't really
want to dive into the whole issue about individual

00:38:36.249 --> 00:38:39.710
versus group selectionism, but I just have
one sort of top-level question-

00:38:39.710 --> 00:38:40.710
&gt;&gt;Dr. Jonathan Haidt: Sure.

00:38:40.710 --> 00:38:45.390
&gt;&gt;male #1: -which is, do you think it's necessary
to invoke group selectionism to explain the

00:38:45.390 --> 00:38:47.210
human propensity for hivish behavior?

00:38:47.210 --> 00:38:49.299
&gt;&gt;Dr. Jonathan Haidt: Well yes, a great question.

00:38:49.299 --> 00:38:52.229
Is it necessary to invoke group selection?

00:38:52.229 --> 00:38:54.000
I think it's not necessary.

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:57.759
There are some very clever explanations as
to why we're so groupish, that rely on individual

00:38:57.759 --> 00:38:58.759
level selection.

00:38:58.759 --> 00:39:03.670
That is individuals who could show off that
they were good team players would be rewarded

00:39:03.670 --> 00:39:06.680
and trusted more and therefore they would
benefit.

00:39:06.680 --> 00:39:11.690
But part of the reason why I'm attracted to
ideas about multi-level selection that is:

00:39:11.690 --> 00:39:14.609
human nature was shaped in part by group versus
group competition, is that there's all this

00:39:14.609 --> 00:39:19.930
weird stuff we do that's very hard to explain
as something that will redound to my personal

00:39:19.930 --> 00:39:20.930
benefit.

00:39:20.930 --> 00:39:26.769
For example, after 9/11 there was sort of
the 'rally around the flag' effect.

00:39:26.769 --> 00:39:31.670
And it's kind of hard to explain that people
who rally around the flag and had this urge

00:39:31.670 --> 00:39:38.109
to support the leader that they beat out the
other ones who had less of that urge.

00:39:38.109 --> 00:39:41.509
A better example I think would be the urge
to kill traitors and apostates.

00:39:41.509 --> 00:39:43.019
So what you do with it.

00:39:43.019 --> 00:39:46.009
A traitor is worse than an enemy, in many
religious books and in many societies.

00:39:46.009 --> 00:39:49.799
A traitor, there's only thing you have to
do with a traitor, you have to kill them.

00:39:49.799 --> 00:39:55.749
Now, do we suppose this urge to kill traitors
came about because long ago individuals who

00:39:55.749 --> 00:39:59.019
killed their traitorous neighbors had more
children than individuals who hung back and

00:39:59.019 --> 00:40:00.220
didn't kill their traitorous neighbors?

00:40:00.220 --> 00:40:04.709
There's just a lot of really tribal groupish
stuff, initiation rites, a lot of weird stuff

00:40:04.709 --> 00:40:09.979
we do that makes perfect sense if you think
that our genes came down to us in part by

00:40:09.979 --> 00:40:13.430
being lodged in successful groups.

00:40:13.430 --> 00:40:18.359
It's being currently fought out, nobody has
a knock down argument but I think the total

00:40:18.359 --> 00:40:23.380
picture of human nature is more consilient
with group selection than with individual

00:40:23.380 --> 00:40:25.190
selection.

00:40:25.190 --> 00:40:33.329
&gt;&gt;male #2: You mentioned searching out and
destroying traitors just now and that kind

00:40:33.329 --> 00:40:35.950
of gets at what I was going to ask.

00:40:35.950 --> 00:40:41.969
What about when the hive sort of goes off
track and I was sitting there thinking a little

00:40:41.969 --> 00:40:43.839
about like Salem witch trials.

00:40:43.839 --> 00:40:49.930
You mentioned bullies in school, what happens
when you have a mob?

00:40:49.930 --> 00:40:51.799
A hive turns into a mob?

00:40:51.799 --> 00:40:53.359
&gt;&gt;Dr. Jonathan Haidt: Right, right.

00:40:53.359 --> 00:40:57.239
So I take an ecological view of human evolution.

00:40:57.239 --> 00:41:03.029
That is if you think about a total ecosystem
and there's lots of niches then there all

00:41:03.029 --> 00:41:05.249
these creatures in the niches.

00:41:05.249 --> 00:41:09.529
Most of those creatures are individual animals
but some of them are groups.

00:41:09.529 --> 00:41:15.089
So if we think about religion, so in my book
I developed at great lengths ideas from David

00:41:15.089 --> 00:41:16.559
Sloan Wilson and others.

00:41:16.559 --> 00:41:20.910
That religion is an adaptation for binding
groups together for intergroup conflict.

00:41:20.910 --> 00:41:26.680
That means that religion in its original tribal
form is very much about getting people to

00:41:26.680 --> 00:41:30.829
trust each other, develop virtues that will
help maximize their productivity and especially

00:41:30.829 --> 00:41:35.130
make them more fit, or at least wipe out or,
at least, out compete neighboring groups.

00:41:35.130 --> 00:41:36.640
Not a very pretty picture.

00:41:36.640 --> 00:41:41.359
And in many parts of the world, as the new
atheists love to document, religions look

00:41:41.359 --> 00:41:42.829
sort of that way.

00:41:42.829 --> 00:41:46.740
But in the American ecosystem, things are
very, very different.

00:41:46.740 --> 00:41:49.140
In America, we've had a free market in religion
since the beginning.

00:41:49.140 --> 00:41:54.299
And especially for Protestants who shift around
quite a lot, between sects.

00:41:54.299 --> 00:41:57.829
So they all have to be good at marketing and
they all have to be appealing and if you go

00:41:57.829 --> 00:42:02.119
to a church, and I'm a Jewish atheist but
I assign my students to go to various, you

00:42:02.119 --> 00:42:03.500
know far right or far left churches.

00:42:03.500 --> 00:42:04.969
I had to do it myself.

00:42:04.969 --> 00:42:09.130
You go in there and everyone is so welcoming,
so nice wherever you go.

00:42:09.130 --> 00:42:13.380
In the American ecosystem, nasty tribal religions
don't propagate.

00:42:13.380 --> 00:42:14.940
But nicer ones do.

00:42:14.940 --> 00:42:19.880
So in our ecology, religion actually turns
out to be a great benefit overall.

00:42:19.880 --> 00:42:24.489
So there's a book called "American Grace"
by Putnam and Campbell where they just look

00:42:24.489 --> 00:42:28.410
at whether religions have a net benefit to
society.

00:42:28.410 --> 00:42:30.989
And they conclude that in America at least,
they really, really do.

00:42:30.989 --> 00:42:36.180
So even though this stuff emerged in ways
that could have all kinds of negative externalities,

00:42:36.180 --> 00:42:37.829
depending on the ecosystem, it can actually
be quite positive.

00:42:37.829 --> 00:42:40.010
There are lots of externalities.

00:42:40.010 --> 00:42:44.770
&gt;&gt;female #1: Hi.

00:42:44.770 --> 00:42:48.480
So when Steven Pinker was here, he was talking
about his theory about the history of violence

00:42:48.480 --> 00:42:49.849
and it's declining in human society-

00:42:49.849 --> 00:42:50.849
&gt;&gt;Dr. Jonathan Haidt: -yes-

00:42:50.849 --> 00:42:52.040
&gt;&gt;female #1: - and he brought up this idea
of moral circles-

00:42:52.040 --> 00:42:53.040
&gt;&gt;Dr. Jonathan Haidt: -yes-

00:42:53.040 --> 00:42:55.119
&gt;&gt;female #1:- like that us has sort of expanded
outward in time.

00:42:55.119 --> 00:42:59.730
It used to be maybe just our family, then
just our tribe then our nation and then the

00:42:59.730 --> 00:43:02.109
groups get bigger and bigger.

00:43:02.109 --> 00:43:03.509
And I'm sorry, I'm blanking on the philosopher-

00:43:03.509 --> 00:43:04.509
&gt;&gt;Dr. Jonathan Haidt: -Peter Singer-

00:43:04.509 --> 00:43:05.829
&gt;&gt;female #1: - Peter Singer.

00:43:05.829 --> 00:43:10.630
So how do you think that dovetails with your
idea about groupishness and hivishness?

00:43:10.630 --> 00:43:11.630
&gt;&gt;Dr. Jonathan Haidt: Yes.

00:43:11.630 --> 00:43:12.630
So, groupishness.

00:43:12.630 --> 00:43:13.970
We get more groupish when we're attacked.

00:43:13.970 --> 00:43:18.779
And after 9/11 we got a lot more groupish,
I think everybody thought there's going to

00:43:18.779 --> 00:43:22.529
be anti-Muslim violence and there wasn't,
to the credit of Americans' generally tolerant

00:43:22.529 --> 00:43:23.529
nature.

00:43:23.529 --> 00:43:29.839
But, war and intergroup conflict shrinks the
circle and makes us more competitive whereas

00:43:29.839 --> 00:43:32.499
peace and prosperity lets that sort fade away.

00:43:32.499 --> 00:43:36.950
Also, intergroup contact trade and travel,
which keep going up, thin that out.

00:43:36.950 --> 00:43:40.999
So I think that Pinker is absolutely right,
violence is declining.

00:43:40.999 --> 00:43:44.510
There are many reasons for that and one of
the reasons he cites is actually trade and

00:43:44.510 --> 00:43:45.650
commerce.

00:43:45.650 --> 00:43:51.900
Because trade and commerce makes you not care
at all what those people eat or how they have

00:43:51.900 --> 00:43:52.900
sex.

00:43:52.900 --> 00:43:54.249
Just, do they have the goods and will they
honor their contract?

00:43:54.249 --> 00:43:58.229
And this is why, to this day, Amsterdam is
one of the most tolerant places on earth.

00:43:58.229 --> 00:44:03.019
Because it was the origin of this kind of
new modern global trade.

00:44:03.019 --> 00:44:12.029
So, I think Pinker is right and as the internet
has helped us see more interact with people

00:44:12.029 --> 00:44:14.569
more globally, it is thinning this stuff out.

00:44:14.569 --> 00:44:18.289
The other piece of the story that Pinker mentions
is strengthening institutions.

00:44:18.289 --> 00:44:22.789
This groupishness, this hivishness, works
well to structure groups when there is no

00:44:22.789 --> 00:44:29.130
police forces, no courts but as you get stronger
institutions, you can weaken this tribalism,

00:44:29.130 --> 00:44:30.130
this hivishness.

00:44:30.130 --> 00:44:34.779
And the Scandinavian countries are the forefront
in world history of having effective civil

00:44:34.779 --> 00:44:38.329
institutions and ever decreasing groupishness.

00:44:38.329 --> 00:44:41.089
So it's possible to have a very humane society
without it.

